Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Solomon Nyamson¶

Introduction¶

This project explores the Proper loan dataset, which is Americas first marketplace lending platform, with over $9 billion in funded loans. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, borrower employment status, borrower credit history, and the latest payment information.

The project goes further to summarize the characteristics of variables that can affect the loan status and to get some ideas about the relationships among multiple variables using summary statistics and data visualizations.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, borrower employment status, borrower credit history, and the latest payment information. The dataFrame called data was created out the original dataset that contains 13 features of each loan and 113,937 rows. This dataset will be further explored by using summary statistics and data visualizations to highlight the traits of variables that can influence the loan status and to get insight into the relationships between various variables.

The features included in the dataset are:

Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.

LoanStatus: Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.

ListingKey: Unique key for each listing, same value as the 'key' used in the listing object in the API.

BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.

BorrowerRate: The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.

EstimatedReturn: The estimated return assigned to the listing at the time it was created. Estimated return is the difference between the Estimated Effective Yield and the Estimated Loss Rate. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.

ProsperRating: allow potential investors to easily consider a loan applications level of risk since it represents an estimated average annual loss rate range for an investor assigned between AA - HR.

ListingCategory: The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans

EmploymentStatus: The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.

IncomeRange: The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.

StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.

MonthlyLoanPayment: The scheduled monthly loan payment.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The two most crucial factors when applying for a loan are the borrower's interest rate and average percentage rate. Therefore, my study will begin by looking into other factors that have an impact on these two factors. Additionally, I will look into the primary variables that determine a loan's status and, finally, what causes loans to vary based on the original amount.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

To aid in identifying and investigating such relationships, I have created a dataframe called data, which is a subset of the prosper dataset.

The borrower's interest rate (BorrowerRate) and the assigned Prosper rating (ProsperRating-Alpha) will affect the borrower's annual percentage rate (BorrowerAPR) for the loan, as these parameters are used to calculate this last value and will also set the estimated return (EstimatedReturn).

The original loan amount (LoanOriginalAmount) is likely to vary depending on its use (ListingCategory) and the current status (LoanStatus), which could depend on the length, in months, (Term) and the monthly payment (MonthlyLoanPayment), which in turn will depend on the borrower's employment status when applying for the loan (EmploymentStatus) and the borrower's income range, annually (IncomeRange) and monthly (StatedMonthlyIncome).

All this data can help to draw conclusions about the main features of interest in the dataset.

Univariate Exploration¶

The analysis will begin by looking into the factors for the interest rate and annual percentage rate of the borrowers, respectively.

What distinguishes the borrower rate from the borrower APR, and what accounts for the differencesbetween the two?

By Definitions:

The Borrower's Rate (interest rate) refers to the annual cost of a loan to a borrower and is expressed as a percentage. The interest rate does not include fees charged for the loan.

The Borrower's APR is the annual cost of a loan to a borrower. Unlike an interest rate, it includes other charges or fees (such as mortgage insurance, most closing costs, discount points and loan origination fees) to reflect the total cost of the loan.

In statistics and Finance , the Borrowers APR is always expected to be higher than the Borrowers Rate which does not include any fees charged for the loan in question and this implies that the distribution for both variable should be similar with a subtle difference.

Now, I will have a look at the borrower's employment status.

Are all borrowers employed at the time of loan application ?

I will utilize the Inter Quartile Range formula for this since the data is not normally distributed.

In [106]:
# define a function to find all outliers
def find_outliers_IQR(df):

   q1=df.quantile(0.25)

   q3=df.quantile(0.75)

   IQR=q3-q1

   outliers = df[((df<(q1-1.5*IQR)) | (df>(q3+1.5*IQR)))]

   return outliers

Analyzing the Prosper Ratings

Prosper Ratings allows potential investors to easily consider a loan applications level of risk since it represents an estimated average annual loss rate range for an investor assigned between AA HR.

The Prosper Rating is calculated using the borrowers credit score (CreditGrade), obtained from an official reporting agency and the Prosper Score based on the prosper population to get the Annual Loss Rate.

It makes reasonable that the original loan amount, one of the key interest-related variables, has a strong positive association with the variable representing the monthly payment. If the loan amount is bigger, the monthly payment will also be higher. How are both variables impacted by the loan's term (measured in months)? It's also possible that the amount of the monthly payment and the range of incomes are related linearly. Below, these possibilities will be looked at. The annual percentage rate and the interest rate have a negative association, which is likewise to be expected.

However, since the annual percentage rate (BorrowerAPR) and the yearly interest rate (BorrowerRate) have a similar distribution, it is not surprising that the annual percentage rate (BorrowerAPR) is higher than the annual interest rate (BorrowerRate).

# define a function to plot such graphs
def plot_numerical_vars(x, numerical_vars):
    for i in range(len(numerical_vars)):
        var = numerical_vars[i]
        plt.sca(axes[i])
        sb.regplot(
            data = data,
            y = var,
            x = x,
            truncate = False,

  1. The percentage of debts that are either being paid off now or have previously been repaid is very high, and the status of the remaining loans is extremely little. Loans that have already been repaid typically equate to modest sums of money.
  1. The annual percentage rate and interest rate of the borrower are two figures that are directly linked to one another. Prosper uses these figures, together with the expected return, to grade the loan, making it simpler for potential investors to assess the risk of a loan application.
  1. With respect to the monthly payment variable, the borrower's monthly income range, and the loan term, the initial loan amount has a positive linear relationship with each of these variables. However, it has a negative correlation with the borrower's interest rate and annual percentage rate.

Conclusions¶

The relationships between some of the most crucial factors when applying for a loan have been investigated during the course of this study.

  • What influences the annual percentage rate (APR) or interest rate of the borrower?

The distribution of both parameters is quite similar, with the tiny exception that the APR figure, which includes fees, is always greater than the interest rate. The dataset contains a number of parameters that are connected to these two values. The initial loan sum is the first factor. There was found a negative relationship between the the Borrower APR and the Original Loan Amount. This implies that the annual percentage rate (APR) for the borrower will be lower as the Loan Amount Increases.

  • What variations exist in loans based on the size of the initial loan amount?

Loans can be distinguished based on several characteristics rather than the initial loan amount. The term of the loan typically increases proportionately to the loan amount, with larger loans being allowed for 60 months. For this loan, the annual percentage rate (APR) and interest rate for the borrower are inversely related to the loan amount. This implies that interest rates will be higher for smaller loans and vice versa. These two pieces of information are then utilized to determine the monthly payment amount, which likewise rises in proportion to the loan amount. Since the annual income range of the applicant and the initial loan amount are positively correlated, loans are only given to those who can afford them.

  • Does the purpose of a loan a borrower is likely to select during loan application accounts for differences in loan amount?

The rationale or purpose for applying for these loans did not appear to be a differentiating factor, either, as a sizable portion of these loans (76.8%) were approved for business, home improvement, or debt consolidation.

Finally, 89.8% of the loans included in the dataset have either been fully repaid or are in the process of being paid back. Since the smallest loans were typically previously repaid, the original loan amount showed the biggest variation. Nothing else that might be influencing the loan's status has been noticed.
